results.name: Expansion of q^(-1/12)eta(q)eta(q^6)/(eta(q^2)eta(q^3)) in powers of q.
comment: In general, if m > 1 and g.f. = Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^(m*k))/(1 + x^k), then a(n) ~ (-1)^n * exp(Pi*sqrt((m+2)*n/(6*m))) * (m+2)^(1/4) / (4 * (6*m)^(1/4) * n^(3/4)) if m is even and a(n) ~ (-1)^n * exp(Pi*sqrt((m-1)*n/(6*m))) * (m-1)^(1/4) / (2^(3/2) * (6*m)^(1/4) * n^(3/4)) if m is odd. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 31 2015
link: Seiichi Manyama, Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000 (terms 0..5000 from Vaclav Kotesovec)
Vaclav Kotesovec, A method of finding the asymptotics of q-series based on the convolution of generating functions, arXiv:1509.08708 [math.CO], Sep 30 2015, p. 14.
formula: G.f.: 1/(Product_{k>0} (1+x^(2k-1)+x^(4k-2))) = Product_{k>0} (1-x^(6k-1))(1-x^(6k-5)) = Product_{k>0} (1-x^k+x^(2k)) (where 1-x+x^2 is 6th cyclotomic polynomial).
Given g.f. A(x), then B(x)=x*A(x^12) satisfies 0=f(B(x), B(x^2), B(x^4)) where f(u, v, w)=(v^2+u^4)*(v^2+w^4)-2*v^4*(1-v*u^2*w^2).
Expansion of G(x^6) * H(x) - x * G(x) * H(x^6) where G(), H() are Rogers-Ramanujan functions.
mathematica: nmax = 100; CoefficientList[Series[Product[(1 + x^(3*k))/(1 + x^k), {k, 1, nmax}], {x, 0, nmax}], x] (* _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Aug 30 2015 *)
QP = QPochhammer; s = QP[q]*(QP[q^6]/(QP[q^2]*QP[q^3])) + O[q]^100; CoefficientList[s, q] (* _Jean-François Alcover_, Nov 23 2015 *)
